Finding balance has been a goal of mine lately and while I can say I’ve done a good job at living like a normal human again, I will admit my bodybuilding has taken a back seat. 

When my health was a concern earlier last year, I decided to not focus on an end goal and just let my body figure it’s ish out. Ins the meantime, I poured everything into work and it’s kept me very busy (love my girls)

I’ve enjoyed the balance and freedom I’ve allowed myself to have when it has come to food and training, being in other peoples company and my relationship with food BUT I settled into some habits that I often advise against: 

- eating once or twice 
- not getting enough protein in
- eating out for all my meals 

I’m thankful to have gone through what I did because a lot of my food focus tendencies and over eating tendencies are gone, but now I’ve made it a goal of mine to start prioritizing the other aspect of my life that I’ve loved so much for many years 

My goals as of now have consisted of getting to the gym 3-4 times a week and when I do it’s mainly lower body with one occasional upper body day thrown in, eating 3-4 times per day with protein in each meal and eating out less. Still not following a plan or tracking macros but being more mindful of what I’m eating

The stage is still an ultimate goal of mine, but it’s not going anywhere and when I’m ready I’ll be back. Until then I’ve got many other plans to level up on a personal and professional level 😈

Competing is freakin hard on your body.

That isn’t new information, 

but the common misconceptions I’m seeing between general population clients and my prep girlies is something I want to address.

Getting to the necessary body composition to be competitive is going to send your hormones out of wack. 

It’s “common” but it isn’t NORMAL.

Amenorrhea (missing 3 or more periods) is something that needs to be addressed, but it’s not the only signal we should be paying attention to. 

Fluctuations in mood, 

Severe cramping during menstrual cycle, 

Puffiness or inflammation (especially in the face), 

Depression or anxiety, 

Hot flashes, 

Insomnia, 

Brain fog.

All need to be taken note of, and continuous observation of them probably means we need to check what’s going on.

There’s so many more, but these are the most common ones I see.

If you’ve been experiencing some or all of these, but have been writing it off because you’ve been told it’s normal,

Shoot me a DM, “symptoms” & we’ll chat about it some more and I’ll give you some insight 💙🙌🏼

What doctors don’t tell you:

The ‘effects’ from your birth control are not your body’s natural cycle. 

Its exogenous hormones making it appear like your bodies natural cycle. 

I wish this was more widely understood, but women go their whole lives not understanding what their birth controls role truly is. 

So let me explain, the "period" you have on hormonal birth control is not a true period. 

Instead it is called a "withdrawal bleed" referring to the withdrawal of hormones in your pill, and in your body. 

The drop in hormone levels causes the lining of your uterus (the endometrium) to shed. 

This bleeding may be slightly different than the period you had before taking the pill and it also may change over time while taking the pill. 

The hormones in the contraceptive pill stop and prevent your ovaries from preparing and releasing eggs. 

They stop the usual hormonal “cycling”, including ovulation, the typical growth of the endometrium, and the natural period - which is why we do not consider this a real period. 

So while birth control can help regulate the amount of time in between bleeds, is it really regulating it in the way you thought it was?
